# Phase 1: IMU Communication & Cursor Control

**Goal:** Verify I2C communication with the MPU6050 and demonstrate IMU-based cursor movement.

**Hardware needed:** ESP32-S3 + MPU6050 (powered via USB — no motor or boost converter required)

**Status:** ✅ Complete

## Wiring

| MPU6050 Pin | ESP32-S3 GPIO | Notes |
|-------------|---------------|-------|
| SDA | 37 | I2C Bus 1 (Wire) |
| SCL | 38 | I2C Bus 1 (Wire) |
| 3V3 | 3V3 | **Do NOT use VIN** — VIN expects 5V |
| GND | GND | Common ground |

## Files (run in order)

| File | Purpose | How to Run |
|------|---------|------------|
| `a_i2c_scanner.ino` | Scan I2C bus, confirm MPU6050 at 0x68 | Upload → Serial Monitor (115200 baud) |
| `b_IMU_dignostic.ino` | Read WHO_AM_I register, validate sensor health | Upload → Serial Monitor |
| `c_phase1_imu_test4.ino` | Stream raw accel/gyro/temp to serial | Upload → tilt board, observe values |
| `d_phase1_imu_cursor.ino` | Send IMU data over serial for Python cursor control | Upload → keep serial open |
| `e_imu_cursor_control.py` | Read serial IMU data, move system cursor | `python e_imu_cursor_control.py` |

## Pass Criteria

- I2C scanner finds device at address `0x68`
- WHO_AM_I register returns `0x68`
- Accel Z reads ~16384 when board is flat (1g at ±2g range)
- Gyro values spike during rotation, settle to ~0 at rest
- Temperature reads ~25–30°C at room temp
- Python script moves cursor when board is tilted

